  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in the workshops I've run with young mechanics and engineers in Naples. It's that moment when a kid, maybe a girl or a person of color, feels the weight of 'you're not supposed to be good at this,' even before they've started the task. I remember teaching a young woman who was nervous about fixing a car engine because she'd heard her classmates say, 'Girls aren't good with engines.' That fear, that self-doubt, can make someone freeze or give up before they even try. It's not just about being 'less capable'—it's about the psychological burden of being labeled by others. As someone who grew up in a family where formal education wasn't the focus, I know how important it is to create spaces where people don't have to hide their potential. In my own life, I've had to navigate stereotypes about immigrants and mechanics—people who don't fit the 'book-smart' mold. So yes, we absolutely need to address stereotype threat in STEM. The key isn't just to talk about it but to build real, practical support systems. For example, in my shop, I've started pairing students with mentors who share their backgrounds, so they see themselves reflected in the work they're doing. It's about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try, fail, and learn without judgment. When you see a young person who might not have grown up with the confidence to pursue engineering, you can't let them feel like they're being held back by a stereotype. It's a matter of respect, of seeing potential where others see limits.",
